citeinfo.title: AMCO Construction Phase Air Monitoring Points, Oakland CA, 2016, US EPA Region 9

descript.abstract: This feature class contains points depicting locations of air monitor sensors during the construction phase of the EPA non-time critical removal action (NTCRA) at the AMCO Chemical Superfund Site located in Oakland, California. The feature class contains 5 point locations for reference but no longer contains live data.The NTCRA at AMCO addresses the portions of the Site with the highest concentrations of volatile organic compounds (VOCs) that pose a threat to human health or the environment. During the cleanup process, a series of live air monitoring sensors are used to ensure operations are protective of human health. The air monitoring status is available to the public at https://epa.maps.arcgis.com/apps/MapSeries/index.html?appid=2e0a0e3d5cc041feb0c19d9f04327bcb.
descript.purpose:
These data provide support for the EPA non-time critical removal action (NTCRA) at the AMCO Chemical Superfund Site located in Oakland, California to address the portions of the Site with the highest concentrations of volatile organic compounds (VOCs) that pose a threat to human health or the environment. During the cleanup process, a series of live air monitoring sensors are used to ensure operations are protective of human health.
The air monitoring status is available to the public at https://epa.maps.arcgis.com/apps/MapSeries/index.html?appid=2e0a0e3d5cc041feb0c19d9f04327bcb.

This feature class contains points depicting locations of air monitor sensors during the construction phase of the EPA non-time critical removal action (NTCRA) at the AMCO Chemical Superfund Site located in Oakland, California. The feature class contains 5 point locations for reference but no longer contains live data.

The NTCRA at AMCO addresses the portions of the Site with the highest concentrations of volatile organic compounds (VOCs) that pose a threat to human health or the environment. During the cleanup process, a series of live air monitoring sensors are used to ensure operations are protective of human health. The air monitoring status is available to the public at https://epa.maps.arcgis.com/apps/MapSeries/index.html?appid=2e0a0e3d5cc041feb0c19d9f04327bcb.
